# zh-Hant typography — Kai + Baskerville

On Chinese pages, Latin and CJK text use different typefaces. English and French
pages are unchanged (all Baskerville).

## Rules

| Page locale | Chinese / CJK characters | English / French (Latin) text |
|-------------|--------------------------|-------------------------------|
| `zh-Hant`   | Kai (`adobe-kaiti-std`, `--kai-zh`) | Baskerville (`--serif-en`) |
| `en`, `fr`  | — (N/A)                  | Baskerville (`--serif-en`) for all text |

## Implementation

- CSS lives in `src/styles/global.css`.
- On `html[lang="zh-Hant"]`, `--locale-font` uses the composite `"TCF Zh Locale"`
  family built from `@font-face` blocks with `unicode-range`:
  - Latin ranges → Baskerville stack (`--serif-en`)
  - CJK ranges → Kai stack (`--kai-zh`, loaded via Adobe Typekit on zh pages)
- Fallback stack: `"TCF Zh Locale", var(--serif-en), var(--kai-zh)`.
- Do **not** set a single Kai-only `font-family` on zh pages — that forces Latin
  snippets (hero translations, nav labels, mixed content) into Kai.
- `en` / `fr` pages keep `--locale-font: var(--serif-en)` only.

## Mixed content on zh pages

Hero English/French taglines, language switcher labels (`English`, `Français`),
and any inline Latin in Chinese copy must render in Baskerville automatically via
the composite font — no per-element overrides unless a component hard-codes Kai.

## Verification

On a zh page in DevTools, inspect:

- A Chinese heading → computed `font-family` includes `adobe-kaiti-std`.
- An English/French snippet → computed `font-family` includes `Baskerville`.
